

ðŸ§© Problem â€” Missing Item ID in Chest
ðŸ“Œ Problem Statement
In a Minecraft survival world, a chest is supposed to contain n + 1 uniquely numbered items, each labeled with an ID from 0 to n.
After a Creeper explosion, one item went missing.

You are given an array itemIDs of size n, representing the IDs of the items still present. Each ID is unique and lies within the range 0 to n.
Your task is to find the missing item ID so the storage system can be restored.

ðŸ“¥ Input Format
First line: Integer T, the number of test cases.

For each test case:

One line: Integer n, the number of items present.

Next line: n spaceâ€‘separated integers representing the list itemIDs.

ðŸ“¤ Output Format
For each test case, output a single integer â€” the missing item ID.

ðŸ”’ Constraints
1 <= T <= 1000

1 <= n <= 10,000

All itemIDs are distinct and within range [0, n].

ðŸ§© Sample Input 0
Code
1
3
3 0 1
ðŸ“Œ Sample Output 0
Code
2
ðŸ“ Explanation 0
n = 3 â†’ full range should be [0,3].

Given IDs = [3,0,1].

Missing = 2.

ðŸ§© Sample Input 1
Code
1
2
0 1
ðŸ“Œ Sample Output 1
Code
2
ðŸ“ Explanation 1
n = 2 â†’ full range should be [0,2].

Given IDs = [0,1].

Missing = 2.

ðŸš€ Solution Approach
The sum of numbers from 0..n = n(n+1)/2.

Subtract the sum of given IDs â†’ the difference is the missing number.

Complexity: O(n) per test case.

Space: O(1).

ðŸ§‘â€ðŸ’» C++ Implementation
cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int T; 
    cin >> T; // number of test cases
    while (T--) {
        int n;
        cin >> n;
        long long sumGiven = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            int id;
            cin >> id;
            sumGiven += id;
        }
        long long sumExpected = 1LL * n * (n + 1) / 2; // sum of 0..n
        cout << (sumExpected - sumGiven) << "\n";
    }
    return 0;
}
âš¡ Complexity
Time: O(n) per test case.

Space: O(1).
